#1 Newly-diagnosed, grade 3 out of 4, infiltrating, synchronous adenocarcinoma of the colon
At this point the patient has had appropriate staging evaluation by her outside providers.  We do have a copy of both the CT abdomen and pelvis and PET scan done at an outside institution.  We will have our radiologists interpret both of those films and better clarify extent of tumor involvement.  She has previously had CBC, electrolytes, LFTs done at an outside institution, and thus, we will not repeat those.  If you would like to see those exact values, they are in the HPI section of this note.  She did have a CEA that was normal at 1.2 July 29, 2010.  At this point we will refer her to Colorectal Surgery for further evaluation.  She will need surgical intervention and then possible chemotherapy and radiation.  We will also consider referral to Medical Oncology pending surgical results.
From a premedical anesthesia evaluation, the patient will undergo an EKG today and will get a chest x-ray.  Her labs have already been mentioned above in the HPI section.  She has had anesthesia with her previous hysterectomy in 1991 with no difficulties.  She has no family history of prolonged bleeding or abnormal bleeding.  She also has no personal history of any bleeding disorders.  She can climb 2 flights of stairs with no difficulty.  I see no reason why she should not be able to proceed directly to surgery pending the chest x-ray and EKG results.
#2 Possible Lynch syndrome
Due to the fact that she has a family history of colon cancer in her father and a sister with uterine cancer, I think it is reasonable to consider this diagnosis.  We will do a urine cytology to rule-out any bladder neoplasms.  In addition, we will consider referral to Medical Genetics for further evaluation.  We will have her outside block sent to Saint Lukes Living County Memorial Hospital and reviewed for specific Lynch syndrome abnormalities.  Depending on results, her children may need their own evaluation.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

